    public class DJICamera
extends DJIObject

    DJI Camera Base Class

    The base class of the DJI drone's camera. The functions in DJICamera are designed to enable developers to get and set camera parameters, take photos, record video, and retreive media files from the SD card.
    This class is to be used through the entire photo and video capturing process, from adjusting camera settings to viewing, downloading and/or editing media files.
    Version:
    V2.4.0
    Author:
    DJI Software

      • startUpdateTimer

        public boolean startUpdateTimer(int intervel)
        Starts the camera's update timer. While the update timer is running, the SDK will request information about the status of the camera from the aircraft, at regular intervals defined by the interval parameter.
        This information is handled through relevant callback interfaces in DJICamera. Not all callbacks handle the update information. Generally, callbacks handling information about camera's state are those that are called according to this update timer.

        Precondition:
        The update timer must not have been started yet, or been stopped with stopUpdateTimer.
        Post Condition:
        The SDK will receive regular information about the state of the camera, allowing developers to monitor the camera's actions.

      • stopUpdateTimer

        public boolean stopUpdateTimer()
        Stops the camera's update timer.

        Pre Condition:
        The camera's update timer must first be started with startUpdateTimer.
        Post Condition:
        The SDK will no longer request information from the aircraft about the state of its camera.
        Returns:
        boolean True if the update timer has been successfully stopped. False otherwise.

      • destory

        public void destory()
        Releases data associated with the current instance of the camera. It is important that developers call destroy() after they are done using the aircraft's camera, else memory will continue to be used, unnecessarily.

      • onVideoRecv

        public static void onVideoRecv(byte[] videoBuffer,
                               int size)
        Video data update callback. Used with the DJIReceivedVideoDataCallBack, which is called every time the mobile device receives a packet of video data from the aircraft, during live streaming.
        We recommend sending this data to a DjiGLSurfaceView, a widget provided by the SDK to handle video stream data. Use the provided setDataToDecoder function on a DjiGLSurfaceView object to display the video stream on a mobile device.
        H.264, or also called MPEG-4 Part 10, Advanced Video Coding (MPEG-4 AVC) is a video coding format that is currently one of the most commonly used formats for the recording, compression, and distribution of video content.
        Parameters:
        videoBuffer - H.264 video data buffer. Please don't free the buffer after it has been used. The units for the video buffer is bytes.
        size - Size of the video data packet
        See Also:
        DjiGLSurfaceView

      • getDjiCameraProperty

        public DJICameraProperty getDjiCameraProperty()
        Returns a DJICameraProperty object, a structure which contains the current camera settings, such as its ISO, shutter speed and saturation value. The DJICamera class also contains functions retrieve the individual value of a specific camera setting.
        Functions in this DJICamera class that request a specific DJICamera property will update this instance's DJICameraProperty object, upon which the developer can call getDJICameraProperty to retrieve the updated object .

        Pre Condition:

        Returns:
        DJICameraProperty Contains all camera setting values

      • setDjiCameraFileNameInfoCallBack

        public void setDjiCameraFileNameInfoCallBack(DJICameraFileNameInfoCallBack mCameraFileNameInfoCB)
        Supported only by the Phantom 2 Series
        Sets the camera's file information callback.

        Prcondition:
        You must first define a DJICameraFileNameInfoCallBack object to pass in as a parameter.

        Post Condition:
        Every time the aircraft's camera captures a photo or a video, the DJICameraFileNameInfoCallback interface that was passed in as a parameter will call its onResult function.
        The onResult function takes in a DJICameraFileNamePushInfo object, which provides the name, path and type of media file that was just captured.
        Parameters:
        mCameraFileNameInfoCB - The DJICameraFIleNameInfoCallBack object to set as the callback interface every time the aircraft's camera captures a media file.
        The DJICameraFileNameInfoCallback interface implements an onResult function, which takes in a DJICameraFileNamePushInfo object from the aircraft.
        DJICameraFileNamePushInfo contains the name, path and type of the media file that was just captured.
        See Also:
        DJICameraFileNamePushInfo

      • setReceivedVideoDataCallBack

        public void setReceivedVideoDataCallBack(DJIReceivedVideoDataCallBack mReceivedVideoDataCallBack)
        Set the received video data callback. The callback's onResult function will be called each time a video data packet is received from the aircraft.

        Precondition:
        You must define a DJIReceivedVideoDataCallBack object to pass in as a parameter.

        Post Condition:
        The DJIReceivedVideoDataCallBack object that was passed in as a parameter will call its onResult function when the aircraft sends a stream of video data to the mobile device.
        onResult takes in a packet of video stream data. We recommend sending this data to a DjiGLSurfaceView, a widget provided by the SDK to handle video stream data. Use the provided setDataToDecoder function on a DjiGLSurfaceView object to display the video stream on a mobile device.
        Parameters:
        mReceivedVideoDataCallBack - The execution callback. Implements onResult:

        onResult(DJIError mErr) - mErr is an enum value, indicating the execution result, and if the execution failed, what the error is.
